Exercise 2.1.1: Central tendency
1. compute the mean age of the participants

> age = driving$age
> mean(age)
[1] 29.41176


2. compute the median age of the participants

> age = driving$age
> median(age)
[1] 31


3. compute the modal age of the participants (note what happens when there are multiple modal frequencies)

> modeOf(driving$age)
[1] 22 35 31

Exercise 2.1.2: Spread
1. compute the standard deviation age of the participants

> sd(driving$age)
[1] 7.106853

2. compute the age range of the participants

> range(driving$age)
[1] 15 42

3. compute the interquartile range on the age of the participants

> IQR(age)
[1] 11

4. compute the 10th, 25th, 75th and 90th percentiles for age

> quantile(age, c(.10, .25, .75, .90))
 10%  25%  75%  90%
20.8 24.0 35.0 36.4
Exercise 2.1.3: Tabulation part 1
1. use table() to construct a tabulation of the distractor variable

> table(driving$distractor)

   none   radio toddler
      5       6       6

2. now use table() to cross-tabulate distractor by peak.hour

> table(driving$distractor, driving$peak.hour)
        
          yes no
  none      2  3
  radio     3  3
  toddler   3  3
Exercise 2.1.4: Tabulation part 2
1. use xtabs() to cross-tabulate distractor by peak.hour

> xtabs(~distractor + peak.hour, driving)
          peak.hour
distractor yes no
   none      2  3
   radio     3  3
   toddler   3  3
