2. use aggregate to calculate the mean number of errors in the first test (i.e. errors_time1) broken down by peak.hour and distractor

> aggregate(errors_time1 ~ peak.hour + distractor, driving, mean)
  peak.hour distractor errors_time1
1       yes       none      5.00000
2        no       none      7.00000
3       yes      radio      5.00000
4        no      radio     11.33333
5       yes    toddler     15.66667
6        no    toddler     16.00000
Exercise 2.1.7: Correlations
1. calculate the correlation of the number of errors at time 1 with the number of errors at time 2 using cor()

> cor(driving$errors_time1, driving$errors_time2)
[1] 0.6962821

2. calculate the Spearman correlation for the same variables, again using cor()


> cor(driving$errors_time1, driving$errors_time2, method = "spearman")
[1] 0.671599

3. use correlate() to compute all pairwise correlations.

> correlate(driving)

